I would sure hope that Visual Basic runs faster. Rexx is an interpreted
language. VX-Rexx does not compile programs. VX-Rexx encodes your
rexx file to keep others from seeing your coding, strings, etc. Otherwise,
it use the Rexx interpretor in OS/2 to do it's work. Watcom states they
have chosen this option to make it easy for VX-Rexx users to gain from
the object extensions that IBM is planning to put in VX-Rexx.

I've scratched the surface here. We've used VX-Rexx at my government
agency since it was first released and all I can say is that we are one
satisified customer. It has done everything we wanted it to do and the
developed applications have proved to be very dependable in a real-time
mission critical enviroment. I hope you'll post your little "test" to 
comp.lang.rexx. I'm sure the folks from Watcom would like to see it and 
formulate a reply.

